goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of unemployment rate across all industries in a specific year and identify any outliers.

goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the relationship between the number of unemployed individuals and the unemployment rate and identify any patterns or trends.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    data = data.sort_values(by='date')
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='date', y='rate', data=data, color='blue')
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries from 2000 to 2010?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y')
    data = data.groupby(['year', 'series'])['rate'].mean().reset_index()
    data = data.sort_values(by=['year', 'rate'], ascending=False)
    data = data.groupby('year').head(1)
    sns.set(style="whitegrid")
    ax = sns.barplot(x="year", y="rate", hue="series", data=data)
    ax.set(xlabel='Year', ylabel='Unemployment Rate')
    ax.axhline(y=data['rate'].max(), color='r', linestyle='--', label='Max Rate: {:.2f}'.format(data['rate'].max()))
    ax.legend(loc='upper left')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['rate'])]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='rate', hue='year', kde=True, ax=ax, multiple='stack', palette='viridis')
    ax.set_xlabel('Unemployment Rate')
    ax.set_ylabel('Count')
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of unemployment rate across all industries in a specific year?')
    ax.legend(title='Year', loc='upper right')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y')
    sns.scatterplot(x='count', y='rate', data=data, hue='year', palette='viridis')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between the number of unemployed individuals and the unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Number of unemployed individuals')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment rate')
    plt.legend(title='Year', loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['month'] = data['date'].dt.month
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    sns.boxplot(x='month', y='rate', data=data, hue='series')
    plt.title('How does the unemployment rate vary across different months within a year for a specific industry?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.legend(title='Industry', loc='upper right')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
